\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw15\brsp20 \nowidctlpar\ul\b\i Description:                                                                                                             \par
\pard\nowidctlpar\ulnone\b0\i0 Luckily everything has settled down now. I am glad that I did not get killed in the \par
process. Just when I think it\rquote s time to settle down as a rich man with a new name... \par
I never did get a penny of Constantine\rquote s one million gold pieces that he had boastfully \par
promised, nor the incredible treasures found by the Mechanists. I\rquote ve already \par
re-accepted my life of sneaking through town again to earn my living. \par
But one morning, fate knocked on my door \endash  in the shape of a unexpected visitor. \par
My dagger was ready, but when I opened the door a little, no one was there. I was \par
about to return when I noticed a sealed letter on the floor. I looked around for \par
someone, again, nobody was there. \par
\par
I opened the letter. \par
\par
Hm, it seems I have a pen pal now. Not only that, it\rquote s the keeper who put me up when \par
I was a child. He is asking for help since he is trapped in some mansion. Well, I should \par
be thankful, yet, his sudden request is strange. Absorbed in thoughts, I rumpled the \par
paper, collected my tools and went out into town. The market was a good shortcut. \par
Big crowds, easy for one to get lost in a sea of people. Too many for the Watch \par
to keep an eye on. And then it happened. \ldblquote Freeze Taffer!\rdblquote  \ldblquote Don\rquote t move!\rdblquote  \par
An ambush. I decided from then on to stay away from \lquote merchants\rquote  with knives.\par
\par
Well, well, well, if it isn\rquote t my old friend Reuben. Apparently, he was fed up with my \par
impertinent behaviour and not only made his guys hound me, but also the City Watch \par
and the Hammerites. With a little help of my tools I was able to escape. \par
A flash bomb and a speed potion were all I needed to get the hell away from there. \par
But I knew they would be looking for me, and the streets would be swarming with \par
cops. Hiding in some dark corner I was able to rethink Orins letter. I had to \par
agree, Lord Duncan\rquote s mansion could not be worse than the streets. Furthermore, \par
visiting an estate at daylight is some difference to my habitual night tours.\par
\par
